SonarQube Cloud (formerly SonarCloud) is a SaaS code analysis tool designed to detect coding issues in 30+ languages, frameworks, and IaC platforms. Your code is checked against an extensive set of rules that cover many attributes of code, such as maintainability, reliability, and security issues, on each merge/pull request.

For those requiring US-based hosting, [SonarQube Cloud US](https://sonarqube.us/) offers the perfect alternative. If you need data residency outside the US or within the EU, [SonarQube Cloud](https://sonarcloud.io/) with this GitHub app is the ideal solution.

SonarQube Cloud integrates seamlessly into your GitHub workflow and provides clear guidance for resolving any code quality and security issues detected. The majority of popular languages can be analyzed automatically; no configuration is required!

With [SonarQube Cloud](https://sonarcloud.io/github), you get:

-   Fast, precise static analysis and feedback on your code
    
-   Support for popular languages, frameworks, and IaC tools
    
-   Free analysis for open-source projects and private projects up to max 50k LoC
    
-   Automatic analysis of pull requests and branches with results reported inline
    
-   IDE Support with [SonarQube for IDE](https://www.sonarsource.com/products/sonarlint/) integration
    
-   Quality Gate (added as a GitHub check) acting at two different levels - first, preventing you from merging pull requests that contain issues - and later, helping you to release only clean, safe code
    
-   Sign up for SonarQube free tier and begin scanning your private and public repositories
    

A [GitHub Action](https://github.com/marketplace/actions/sonarcloud-scan) is available in the marketplace to make it easy for you (for projects where automatic analysis isn't available). SonarQube Cloud also integrates smoothly with Jenkins, CircleCI, TravisCI, CirrusCI, and many other tools.

A free tier is available that allows you to explore the benefits of SonarQube Cloud using your public and private repositories. We also provide a no-commitment, [14-day trial](https://www.sonarsource.com/products/sonarcloud/signup/) of SonarQube Cloud Team for unlimited team members, up to 1.9M LoC, AI CodeFix recommendations, and more. No need to speak with a sales rep or request a license key - get automatic code analysis results on your private projects in minutes! Want to see more examples of SonarCloud in action? You can [explore current Open Source projects in SonarCloud](https://sonarcloud.io/explore/projects?sort=-analysis_date) that are using the [Clean as You Code](https://www.sonarsource.com/solutions/our-unique-approach/) methodology.

pull_request.body:
# ðŸ“¦ Repository Management Commands

Adds complete repository management to the Runtipi CLI for managing app stores and to avoid command running while outside main runtipi dirctory.

## ðŸ†• What's New

### Commands Added
```bash
runtipi repo list                    # Show all repositories
runtipi repo add <name> <url>        # Add new repository  
runtipi repo remove <name>           # Remove repository
runtipi repo update                  # Update all repositories
```

### Example Usage
```bash
# Add the community app store
runtipi repo add community-apps https://github.com/runtipi/runtipi-appstore

# List all configured repositories
runtipi repo list

# Update repositories to get latest apps
runtipi repo update
```

## ðŸ”’ Security Improvement

**Directory Validation**: The CLI now enforces execution only within a valid Runtipi installation directory. Commands will fail with a clear error message if run outside the proper Runtipi folder, preventing accidental execution in wrong locations.

## âš ï¸ Important Notice

> **Repository Remove Behavior**: The API currently returns `200 OK` even when trying to remove non-existent repositories. The CLI will show "success" but users should check Runtipi logs for actual removal status. This behavior is documented in the code with a comment for future reference if the API behavior changes.

## ðŸ”§ Technical Changes

- **New file**: `internal/commands/repo.go` - Repository command implementation
- **Updated**: `internal/types/args.go` - Added `RepoArgs` and `RepoCommand` types  
- **Updated**: `cmd/runtipi/main.go` - Integrated repo commands + directory validation
- **Enhanced**: Directory validation logic using `.env` file detection

## âœ¨ Features

- âœ… **Smart error handling** - Clear messages for duplicate names, invalid URLs
- âœ… **Beautiful output** - Formatted repository listing with emojis and status  
- âœ… **Cross-platform** - Works on Windows, Linux, and ARM64 (Raspberry Pi)
- âœ… **Consistent UX** - Follows same patterns as existing app commands
- âœ… **Directory safety** - Prevents execution outside Runtipi installations
- âœ… **API quirks documented** - Known limitations clearly marked for future maintenance

<!-- This is an auto-generated comment: release notes by coderabbit.ai -->

## Summary by CodeRabbit

- New Features
  - Added CLI repository management: repo update, repo list, repo add [name] [url], repo remove [name].
  - Repo listing displays name, URL, and enabled status with clearer progress indicators.
  - Added support for reading configuration from a .env file (e.g., ROOT_FOLDER_HOST).
  - Improved, user-friendly error messages for repository operations (e.g., missing, duplicate, or clone errors).

<!-- end of auto-generated comment: release notes by coderabbit.ai -->

issue.title: Bug: Navbar links hidden on mobile
issue.body:
On mobile devices, the navbar links are hidden and cannot be accessed by users. This makes the navigation unusable on smaller screens.  

**Expected Behavior:**  
On mobile view, the navbar should display a **hamburger icon**. When clicked, the icon should **toggle the menu** (open/close) so users can access all navigation links.  

**Steps to Reproduce:**  
1. Open the website on a mobile device or in responsive mode.  
2. Observe that the navigation links are not visible.  
3. No hamburger icon is available to toggle the menu.  

**Proposed Fix:**  
- Add a hamburger icon that appears only on mobile view.  
- Implement toggle functionality so the menu opens and closes when the icon is clicked.

issue.body:
Signed-off-by: Igor Bezukh <ibezukh@redhat.com>

Runbook PR: https://github.com/openshift/runbooks/pull/318

**What this PR does / why we need it**:
In an upgrade scenario it can happen that duplicate wasp-agent
deployment can appear, since previous wasp-agent deployments
were manual and in a different namespace.
Therefore in order to make sure the user is aware of it we
are adding an alert which will rely on the a metric of memory
overcommit percentage and presence of wasp namespace.

**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**
It seems as though emulating a CDJ has some limitations around the number that can be in session to access track data. There may be a way to do this via emulating prodjlinkbridge.

**Describe the solution you'd like**
Bridgeâ€™s announced device â€œIDâ€ in vendor messages is 0x83 (131) â€” a non-player class and it is able to retrieve the track and meta information without being a CDJ. I'd be curious of this.

**Additional context**
I think it would be useful to figure out how this works and maybe make this project even better.
